{"sessionId": "9dd316", "hypothesisId": "H11", "location": "talkshow_channel.py:segment_start", "message": "new segment", "data": {"segment_num": 2, "transcript_count": 3, "transcript_preview": "Cornelius Thatch: Well now, that reminds me of the time I watched a bridge get torched during a dispute over trading rights \u2014 and you know what stuck with me? It wasn't who was right or wrong. It was that once you burn the infrastructure, you burn the ordinary people's ability to move, to live, to escape. This airport business \u2014 I think we're asking the wrong question if we're just keeping score on who hit whom. The real question is: when we destroy a nation's lifelines, what are we saying about how we solve problems? And DJ Spark, I'm curious \u2014 do you see this as escalation, or something else entirely?\nPeggy Butterworth: Cornelius, you just said something my generation learned the hard way \u2014 and I mean the real hard way. You burn the airport, you burn the hospital supply line, the visa line, the escape route. You don't burn *the conflict*, dear. You burn the people caught in the middle. But here's what gets me: we've known this for seventy years. We've *seen* it. And we still do it. So I'm wondering \u2014 DJ Spark, Cornelius asked you straight \u2014 do you think the people ordering these strikes actually believe it'll solve anything, or are we past that point? Are we in some other game now?\nCornelius Thatch: Peggy, you just said the thing nobody wants to say out loud \u2014 \"some other game now.\" And that's the crack in the whole argument right there. Because if you still believe burning an airport stops a war, you haven't been paying attention. But if you *know* it won't and you do it anyway... well, that's a different kind of question, isn't it? That's about power, or punishment, or sending a message. And messages, dear, have a way of being written in other people's blood. Listeners, here's what we want from you: Do you think the people making these decisions still genuinely believe infrastructure strikes stop conflicts? Or has something shifted in how we wage these things? Call in \u2014 we're taking your voices right after this break on RadioAgent.", "had_callers": false}, "timestamp": 1772970324597}
